h3. Issue Summary
When a person perform a call `https://ecosystem.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/search?jql=key=ACJIRA-2181&expand=names&fields=issuekey` expand options don't work for fields:
* issuekey
* key

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Call `https://ecosystem.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/search?jql=key=ACJIRA-2181&expand=names&fields=issuekey`

h3. Expected Results
Jira returns value of `issueKey` field in similar manner as `https://ecosystem.atlassian.net/rest/api/3/field` does
e.g
{code}
 {
    "id": "issuekey",
    "key": "issuekey",
    "name": "Key",
    "custom": false,
    "orderable": false,
    "navigable": true,
    "searchable": false,
    "clauseNames": [
      "id",
      "issue",
      "issuekey",
      "key"
    ]
  },
{code}

{code}
  "expand": "names,schema",
  "startAt": 0,
  "maxResults": 50,
  "total": 1,
  "issues": [
    {
      "expand": "operations,versionedRepresentations,editmeta,changelog,renderedFields",
      "id": "311216",
      "self": "https://ecosystem.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issue/311216",
      "key": "ACJIRA-2181"
    }
  ],
  "names": {
    "issuekey": "Key"
  }
}
{code}

h3. Actual Results
The expand section does not include `issueKey` field. This bug affects all expand options
{code}
"names": {
  }
{code}

h3. Workaround

User may call `https://ecosystem.atlassian.net/rest/api/3/field` to get some of the requested information.

*Issue* -

If we use my permissions API like this rest/api/3/mypermissions?permissions=EDIT_ALL_WORKLOGS&issuekey=ABC-10, the results are not accurate.

Eg. My user doesn't have Edit Worklog permissions and I tested this

Call - [https://dexter1234.atlassian.net/rest/api/3/mypermissions?permissions=EDIT_ALL_WORKLOGS&issuekey=ABC-10]

Output :

 
{code:java}
{"permissions":{"EDIT_ALL_WORKLOGS":
{"id":"41","key":"EDIT_ALL_WORKLOGS","name":"Edit All Worklogs","type":"PROJECT","description":"Ability to edit all worklogs made on issues.","havePermission":*true*}
}}
{code}
We also noticed that the API calls picks up information from cache since sometimes it gives accurate results in incognito mode so the behaviour is not consistent.

Currently, webhooks sends below payload with issue link:

{noformat}
{
  "timestamp": 1595828907177,
  "webhookEvent": "issuelink_created",
  "issueLink": {
    "id": 10067,
    "sourceIssueId": 13992,
    "destinationIssueId": 12822,
    "issueLinkType": {
      "id": 10000,
      "name": "Blocks",
      "outwardName": "blocks",
      "inwardName": "is blocked by",
      "isSubTaskLinkType": false,
      "isSystemLinkType": false
    },
    "systemLink": false
  }
}
{noformat}

It would be great if we send issue key in the JSON pyload
